the now-infamous military prison was built around them. Guantanamo became their home for the next seven years. They endured torture and harassment and force-feedings and beatings, all the while not knowing if they would ever see their families again. They had no opportunity to argue their innocence until 2008, when the Supreme Court issued a landmark ruling in their case, Boumediene v. Bush, confirming Guantanamo detainees' constitutional right to challenge their detention in federal court. Weeks later, the George W. Bush-appointed federal judge who heard their case, stunned by the absence of evidence against them, ordered their release. Now living in Europe and rebuilding their lives, Lakhdar and Mustafa are finally free to share a story that every American ought to know. Learn more at witnessesbook.com or donate to a crowdsourced restitution fund at GoFundMe.com/witnesses.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aDetention of personszCubazGuantánamo Bay Naval Base. 0aPrisoners of warxAbuse ofzCubazGuantánamo Bay Naval Base. 0aPrisoners of warxLegal status, laws, etc.zCubazGuantánamo Bay Naval Base. 0aWar on Terrorism, 2001-2009xPrisoners and prisons, American. 4aBoumediene v. Bush. 4aGuantanamo. 4adetainee. 4ahabeas corpus. 4ainnocence. 4ainterrogation. 4aprisoners' rights. 4arendition. 4awar on terror. 4awrongful imprisonment. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Personal Memoirs.2bisacsh1 aAit Idir, Mustafa, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aList, Kathleen1 aNorland, Daniel Hartnett, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRose, Jeffrey, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360211340uhttps:/